50|$|Specialist <b>joysticks,</b> classed as an assistive {{technology}} pointing device, {{are used to}} replace the computer mouse for people with fairly severe physical disabilities. Rather than controlling games, these <b>joysticks</b> control the pointer. They are often useful to people with athetoid conditions, such as cerebral palsy, who find them easier to grasp than a standard mouse. Miniature <b>joysticks</b> are available for people with conditions involving muscular weakness such as muscular dystrophy or motor neurone disease as well. They are also used on electric powered wheelchairs for control since they are simple and effective {{to use as a}} control method.|$|R
